(136, 7, 'Why Blockchain is Hard Why Blockchain is Hard Why Blockchain is Hard vvvvvvvvvvv', 'The hype around blockchain is massive. To hear the blockchain hype train tell it, blockchain will now: Solve income inequality Make all data secure ', '2020-01-23 11:00:56', 'PUBLISH', 'PUBLIC', NULL, '<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"587\" height=\"416\" /></p>\r\n<p id=\"6775\" class=\"gx gy ar bj gz b ha hb hc hd he hf hg hh hi hj hk\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 2em 0px -0.46em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84); line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.004em; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, \'Times New Roman\', Times, serif; font-size: 21px; background-color: #ffffff;\" data-selectable-paragraph=\"\">So what is a blockchain? Technically speaking, a blockchain is a linked list of blocks and a block is a group of ordered transactions. If you didn&rsquo;t understand the last sentence, you can think of a blockchain as a subset of a database, with a few additional properties.</p>\r\n<p id=\"995f\" class=\"gx gy ar bj gz b ha hb hc hd he hf hg hh hi hj hk\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 2em 0px -0.46em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84); line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.004em; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, \'Times New Roman\', Times, serif; font-size: 21px; background-color: #ffffff;\" data-selectable-paragraph=\"\"><mark class=\"pl pm ld\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; cursor: pointer; background-color: rgba(12, 242, 143, 0.2); color: currentcolor;\">The main thing distinguishing a blockchain from a normal database is that there are specific rules about how to put data into the database. That is, it cannot conflict with some other data that&rsquo;s already in the database (consistent), it&rsquo;s append-only (immutable), and the data itself is locked to an owner (ownable), it&rsquo;s replicable and available. Finally, everyone agrees on what the state of the things in the database are (canonical) without a central party (decentralized).</mark></p>\r\n<p id=\"c847\" class=\"gx gy ar bj gz b ha hb hc hd he hf hg hh hi hj hk\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 2em 0px -0.46em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84); line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.004em; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, \'Times New Roman\', Times, serif; font-size: 21px; background-color: #ffffff;\" data-selectable-paragraph=\"\">It is this last point that really is the holy grail of blockchain. Decentralization is very attractive because it implies there is&nbsp;<em class=\"jf\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit;\">no single point of failure</em>. That is, no single authority will be able to take away your asset or change &ldquo;history&rdquo; to suit their needs. This immutable audit trail where you don&rsquo;t have to trust anyone is the benefit that everyone that&rsquo;s playing with this technology is looking for. This benefit, however, come at a great cost.</p>\r\n<h1 id=\"7a19\" class=\"ht hu ar bj bi hv et hw ev hx hy hz ia ib ic id ie\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 1.95em 0px -0.28em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84); font-family: medium-content-sans-serif-font, \'Lucida Grande\', \'Lucida Sans Unicode\', \'Lucida Sans\', Geneva, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.12; letter-spacing: -0.022em; font-size: 34px; background-color: #ffffff;\" data-selectable-paragraph=\"\">The Cost of Blockchains</h1>\r\n<p id=\"833b\" class=\"gx gy ar bj gz b ha if hc ig he ih hg ii hi ij hk\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0.86em 0px -0.46em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84); line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.004em; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, \'Times New Roman\', Times, serif; font-size: 21px; background-color: #ffffff;\" data-selectable-paragraph=\"\">The immutable audit trail uncontrolled by any single party is certainly useful, but there are many costs to create such a system. Let&rsquo;s examine some of the issues.</p>\r\n<h2 id=\"71ca\" class=\"jg hu ar bj bi hv jh ji jj jk jl jm jn jo jp jq jr\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 1.72em 0px -0.31em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84); font-family: medium-content-sans-serif-font, \'Lucida Grande\', \'Lucida Sans Unicode\', \'Lucida Sans\', Geneva, Arial, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -0.022em; line-height: 1.18; font-size: 26px; background-color: #ffffff;\" data-selectable-paragraph=\"\">Development is stricter and slower</h2>\r\n<p id=\"3349\" class=\"gx gy ar bj gz b ha if hc ig he ih hg ii hi ij hk\" style=\"box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0.86em 0px -0.46em; color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.84); line-height: 1.58; letter-spacing: -0.004em; font-family: medium-content-serif-font, Georgia, Cambria, \'Times New Roman\', Times, serif; font-size: 21px; background-color: #ffffff;\" data-selectable-paragraph=\"\">Creating a provably consistent system is not an easy task. A small bug could corrupt the entire database or cause some databases to be different than other ones. Of course, a corrupted or split database no longer has any consistency guarantees. Furthermore, all such systems have to be designed from the outset to be consistent. There is no &ldquo;move fast and break things&rdquo; in a blockchain. If you break things, you lose consistency and the blockchain becomes corrupted and worthless.</p>', '', '', 1);
